"""
mkt-original — Genesis chapters 25-26
Run: python3 scripts/zc-original-genesis-25-26.py

Key linguistic coverage:
- Ch 25: toledot structural markers (v19); athar vs palal for prayer (v21); darash for
  oracle inquiry (v22); ratsats — violent struggle (v22); two-nations oracle (v23) and
  its Paul/Romans 9 implications; admoni/sear wordplays on Edom/Seir (v25); yaaqov/aqev
  heel-etymology and aqav supplanting (v26); bekorah/bekhor birthright vocabulary (v31-33);
  bazah — despised (v34) and its Heb 12:16 echo
- Ch 26: famine-parallel to ch 12 (v1); four-term obedience vocabulary in v5 (shama/shamar/
  mitsvah/chuqqah/torah); tsakhaq/metsakhaq wordplay on Isaac's name (v8); me'ah shearim
  hundredfold (v12); well-naming sequence Esek/Sitnah/Rehoboth (v20-22); ra'oh ra'inu
  emphatic infinitive (v28); shiv'ah/Beersheba oath-etymology (v33); merat ruakh — grief
  idiom (v35)
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

GENESIS_ORIGINAL = {
  "25": {
    "1": """<p><strong>Qĕṭûrāh</strong> — "Keturah," Abraham's second wife taken after Sarah's death. The name likely derives from a root related to incense or smoke (<em>qāṭar</em>, to burn incense). The narrative introduces a tension about her status: here she is called <em>ʾiššāh</em> (wife), but v6 and 1 Chr 1:32 call her a <em>pîlegeš</em> (concubine). The distinction matters legally: a concubine's sons receive gifts (<em>mattānōt</em>, v6) rather than full inheritance. The narrator may preserve two traditions or signal that Keturah held an intermediate status — a secondary wife rather than a slave-concubine like Hagar.</p>""",
    "2": """<p>The six sons of Keturah — Zimran, Jokshan, Medan, <strong>Midyān</strong> (Midian), Ishbak, Shuah — are the genealogical founders of Arabian tribal peoples. Midian becomes particularly significant: the Midianites are enemies of Israel (Num 31; Judg 6-8) but also the family of Moses's father-in-law Jethro (Exod 2:15-22; 3:1). The genealogy places these peoples within the Abrahamic family while explaining why they stand outside the covenant line. The list is formulaic — paratactic names linked by <em>waw</em> — characteristic of genealogical registers throughout Genesis.</p>""",
    "3": """<p><strong>Yoqšān wālad ʾet-Šeḇāʾ wĕʾet-Dĕḏān</strong> — "Jokshan fathered Sheba and Dedan." Sheba (H7614, from <em>šāḇaʿ</em>, seven/oath) is the source of the Sabaean people of Arabia, famous for the Queen of Sheba episode (1 Kgs 10:1-13). Dedan appears in Isaiah (21:13; Isa 60:6) and Ezekiel (27:20; 38:13) as a trading people. The second-generation names Ashurites, Letushites, and Leummites are otherwise unattested — likely small Arabian tribal groups. The genealogy shows that Abraham's blessing extended beyond the covenant line to produce nations throughout the ancient world.</p>""",
    "4": """<p><strong>Bĕnê Miḏyān</strong> — "sons of Midian." The five Midianite sub-groups listed here (Ephah, Epher, Hanoch, Abida, Eldaah) are names that appear in later commercial and political contexts. Ephah is named in Isa 60:6 among the nations bringing gifts of gold and frankincense to Zion. The genealogical formula <em>kol-ʾēlleh bĕnê qĕṭûrāh</em> ("all these were sons of Keturah") closes the section — the same closing formula used for Ishmael's sons in v16 (<em>kol-ʾēlleh bĕnê yišmāʿēl</em>). Both sections frame the non-covenant lines that nonetheless descend from Abraham.</p>""",
    "5": """<p><strong>wayyittēn ʾaḇrāhām ʾet-kol-ʾăšer-lô lĕyiṣḥāq</strong> — "Abraham gave everything he had to Isaac." The verb <em>nātan</em> (gave) combined with <em>kol-ʾăšer-lô</em> (all that he had) is the formulaic language of inheritance transfer (cf. 24:36). This legal act is completed while Abraham is still alive — a form of <em>inter vivos</em> transfer rather than testamentary bequest. The exclusivity of Isaac's inheritance (<em>ʾet-kol</em>, everything) establishes the unambiguous covenant line before Abraham dies, eliminating any dispute after his death about which son is the primary heir.</p>""",
    "6": """<p><strong>mattānōt</strong> — "gifts." The noun <em>mattānāh</em> (H4976) = a gift, something presented rather than owed as a legal right, distinguishing the concubines' sons' portion from Isaac's <em>yeruššāh</em> (inheritance). Abraham sends them <em>qēḏmāh</em> (eastward) — the direction of non-covenant peoples in Genesis: Cain goes east (4:16), the tower builders are in the east (11:2), Lot chooses the east (13:11), and the sons of Keturah settle east. The east is the direction away from the covenant land. <em>Bĕʿôḏennû ḥāy</em> — "while he was still living" — the disposition during lifetime contrasts with inheritance received at death; Abraham settles matters before he dies.</p>""",
    "7": """<p><strong>wĕʾēlleh yĕmê šnê-ḥayyê ʾaḇrāhām</strong> — "These are the days of the years of Abraham's life." The life-summary formula for Abraham (175 years) parallels the genealogical summaries of the pre-flood patriarchs (5:3-32) and Ishmael's summary (v17). The explicit counting of years connects Abraham to the covenant-history framework of Genesis time. 175 = 5 × 5 × 7, which later Jewish tradition noted as a "perfect" number, though the text does not make this observation — the narrator simply records the completeness of the life without embellishment.</p>""",
    "8": """<p><strong>wayyiggwaʿ wayyāmat ʾaḇrāhām bĕśêḇāh ṭôḇāh zāqēn wĕśāḇēʿa wayyēʾāsep ʾel-ʿammāyw</strong> — "Abraham breathed his last and died in good old age, an old man and full of years, and was gathered to his people." The verb <em>gāwaʿ</em> (H1478, to expire, breathe one's last) — a rare verb used predominantly for death in Genesis (25:8,17; 35:29; 49:33) — differs from the common <em>mût</em> (to die); it emphasizes the physical cessation of breath. <em>Śāḇēʿa</em> (satisfied, full) — from <em>śāḇaʿ</em>, to be satisfied/sated — describes a life brought to its natural completion without deficit. <em>Wayyēʾāsep ʾel-ʿammāyw</em> — "gathered to his people" — a distinctive formula for honorable death within the covenant community (also used for Ishmael, 25:17; Isaac, 35:29; Jacob, 49:33; Aaron, Num 20:24; Moses, Num 27:13). The idiom implies existence beyond death — one is gathered to those who preceded him — though the text does not elaborate the mode of that existence.</p>""",
    "9": """<p><strong>wayyiqbĕrû ʾōtô yiṣḥāq wĕyišmāʿēl bānāyw</strong> — "Isaac and Ishmael his sons buried him." The two sons who have been separated since Ishmael's expulsion (ch 21) come together for their father's burial — a reunion the text records without editorial comment. The cave of Machpelah (<em>mĕʿārat hammakpēlāh</em>), purchased by Abraham in Gen 23 from Ephron the Hittite, now fulfills its purpose as the patriarchal burial place. The land purchase was specifically for this — ownership of a burial plot was the tangible beginning of the covenant inheritance in Canaan. Jacob and Leah will also be buried here (49:29-32; 50:13).</p>""",
    "10": """<p><strong>šĕḏēh qānāh ʾaḇrāhām mēʾēt bĕnê-ḥēt šāmmāh qubbar ʾaḇrāhām wĕśārāh ʾišĕtô</strong> — "the field Abraham had purchased from the Hittites — there Abraham was buried, and Sarah his wife." The burial of Abraham with Sarah is the completion of the Machpelah transaction (ch 23). The field (<em>śāḏeh</em>) is specifically the field; the narrator uses the legal term <em>qānāh</em> (purchased, acquired) that was used in the formal transaction of 23:16-18. Abraham's burial "with Sarah his wife" ties the covenant pair together in death as in life — the couple who received the promise together rest together in the covenant land.</p>""",
    "11": """<p><strong>wayĕḇāreḵ ʾĕlōhîm ʾet-yiṣḥāq bĕnô wayyēšeḇ yiṣḥāq ʿim-bĕʾēr laḥay rōʾî</strong> — "God blessed Isaac his son, and Isaac settled near Beer-lahai-roi." The first act after Abraham's death is God's blessing of Isaac — the covenant transfers immediately without interruption. <em>Bĕʾēr laḥay rōʾî</em> ("well of the Living One who sees me") is the well named by Hagar in 16:14 (<em>ʾattāh ʾēl rōʾî</em>, "you are the God who sees"). Isaac settles precisely where Hagar encountered God — the geography is theologically charged: the covenant heir dwells at the place named for the God who sees and provides.</p>""",
    "12": """<p><strong>wĕʾēlleh tôlĕḏōt yišmāʿēl ben-ʾaḇrāhām</strong> — "These are the generations of Ishmael son of Abraham." The <em>tôlĕḏōt</em> formula (H8435, generations/account) marks a major structural division in Genesis — the tenth and final use of the formula before the Jacob cycle begins. The Ishmael genealogy is placed here, between Abraham's death and the Isaac-Jacob narrative, to close out the non-covenant line completely before the covenant story resumes. The specification "son of Abraham, whom Hagar the Egyptian, Sarah's slave, bore to Abraham" rehearses the full genealogical and social context — emphasizing both the Abrahamic connection and the slave-mother status that excluded him from the primary inheritance.</p>""",
    "13": """<p><strong>šĕmôt bĕnê yišmāʿēl bišmōtām lĕtôlĕḏōtām</strong> — "the names of the sons of Ishmael by their names, by their generations." The twelve sons of Ishmael listed in vv13-15 fulfill the promise of 17:20 ("twelve princes shall he father"). The firstborn <em>Nĕḇāyôt</em> (Nebaioth) is linked with Kedar in Isa 60:7 as bringing offerings to YHWH in the eschatological gathering of nations. The number twelve is structurally significant: Ishmael's twelve princes parallel the twelve tribes of Israel (35:22-26) — God's promise to Ishmael is given the same numerical form as his promise to Jacob.</p>""",
    "14": """<p>The names Mishma, Dumah, Massa appear in the list with no commentary in the text. Dumah (H1746, silence) becomes the name of an Edomite region and appears in Isa 21:11 as a place of prophetic oracle. Massa appears in Prov 30:1 and 31:1 as the oracle-source of Agur and Lemuel — if these are Ishmaelite tribal names, two of Proverbs' wisdom contributors may be descendants of Ishmael, broadening the wisdom tradition beyond Israel. The genealogical names are terse but their connections to later OT material give them weight beyond the list itself.</p>""",
    "15": """<p>The final four sons of Ishmael — Hadad, Tema, Jetur, Naphish, Kedemah — represent Arabian tribes documented in Assyrian inscriptions. Tema appears in Job 6:19 and Isa 21:14 as an oasis city and caravan stop. Jetur and Naphish reappear in 1 Chr 5:19-20 as peoples against whom the Transjordanian tribes warred. The specificity of the genealogical names connects the biblical text to the identifiable political geography of the ancient Near East — these are not literary inventions but remembered peoples.</p>""",
    "16": """<p><strong>šĕnêm ʿāśār nĕśîʾim lĕʾummōtām</strong> — "twelve princes according to their clans." <em>Nāśîʾ</em> (H5387, prince, chief, one who lifts/carries) — from the root <em>nāśāʾ</em> (to lift up), signifying a leader who carries responsibility for the group. The word is used for tribal leaders throughout the Pentateuch (Num 1:16; 7:2,10; 34:18). <em>Lĕʾummōtām</em> (according to their clans/peoples) — <em>leʾōm</em> (H3816, a people, clan) appears in the oracle to Rebekah in v23 (<em>ûšĕnê leʾummîm</em>, "two peoples"); the same word is used for Ishmael's descendants and for Jacob/Esau in the womb — suggesting the structural parallelism between the twelve Ishmaelite princes and the twelve Israelite tribes.</p>""",
    "17": """<p><strong>wayyiggwaʿ wayyāmat wayyēʾāsep ʾel-ʿammāyw</strong> — "he breathed his last and died and was gathered to his people." Ishmael's death formula repeats Abraham's almost verbatim (v8): <em>gāwaʿ</em> (expire), <em>mût</em> (die), <em>neeaph ʾel-ʿammāyw</em> (gathered to his people). The identical formula for father and son suggests that Ishmael's end, though outside the covenant line, is an honorable death — the same language of completion is applied. Ishmael's 137 years (vs. Abraham's 175) marks him as fully flourishing without the covenant's full weight. The gathering-to-his-people language implies the same post-mortem continuity as Abraham's death.</p>""",
    "18": """<p><strong>wayyiškon mēḥăwîlāh ʿad-šûr ʾăšer ʿal-pĕnê miṣrayim bōʾăḵāh ʾaššûrāh</strong> — "He settled from Havilah to Shur, which is opposite Egypt, going toward Assyria." The territory described (from Havilah to Shur) matches the wilderness east of Egypt — cf. 1 Sam 15:7 for the same description of Saul's campaign against the Amalekites. <em>ʿAl-pĕnê kol-ʾeḥāyw nāpāl</em> — "He settled in hostility to all his brothers" — the verb <em>nāpal</em> (to fall, settle, live) in the phrase <em>ʿal-pĕnê</em> (over against, in the face of) echoes the earlier oracle about Ishmael: <em>yādô bakkōl wĕyad kōl bô</em> ("his hand against everyone, everyone's hand against him," 16:12). The fulfillment of the wilderness-dweller oracle closes the Ishmael genealogy.</p>""",
    "19": """<p><strong>wĕʾēlleh tôlĕḏōt yiṣḥāq ben-ʾaḇrāhām ʾaḇrāhām hôlîḏ ʾet-yiṣḥāq</strong> — "These are the generations of Isaac son of Abraham — Abraham fathered Isaac." The <em>tôlĕḏōt</em> formula marks the beginning of the Isaac-Jacob narrative as the dominant structural unit. The doubling "Isaac son of Abraham — Abraham fathered Isaac" is often noted as tautological, but it is a deliberate rhetorical emphasis: the covenant line runs specifically through the father-son chain of Abraham → Isaac, not through the Keturah or Hagar lines. The repetition drives home the genealogical and covenantal specificity.</p>""",
    "20": """<p><strong>wĕyiṣḥāq ben-ʾarbāʿîm šānāh bĕqaḥtô ʾet-riqāh bat-bĕtûʾēl hāʾărammî mippaddān ʾărām ʾăḥôt lāḇān hāʾărammî lô lĕʾiššāh</strong> — "Isaac was forty years old when he took Rebekah daughter of Bethuel the Aramean from Paddan Aram, sister of Laban the Aramean, as his wife." The age-marker (40 years) is the narrator's anchor for chronological reckoning. The triple repetition of "Aramean" (<em>ʾărammî</em>) in one verse identifies Rebekah's ethnic origin emphatically — she is from outside Canaan, from the ancestral homeland of the patriarchs in Aram-Naharaim. The specification "sister of Laban the Aramean" introduces Laban, who will be Jacob's antagonist in the Jacob cycle (chs 29-31). Laban's identity is established before Jacob is born.</p>""",
    "21": """<p><strong>wayyeʿtar yiṣḥāq laYHWH lĕnokaḥ ʾišĕtô kî ʿăqārāh hîʾ</strong> — "Isaac prayed to YHWH on behalf of his wife, because she was barren." The verb <em>ʿātar</em> (H6279, to pray, entreat, intercede) is not the common prayer verb <em>pālal</em> or the root of <em>tĕpillāh</em>; <em>ʿātar</em> has a specifically intercessory, entreating nuance — it appears for Moses's plague intercession (Exod 8:8-13,25-30; 9:28-33; 10:17-18) and prophetic intercession (1 Sam 8:6; 12:19). The verb places Isaac in the role of intercessor for his barren wife, as Abraham was for Abimelech's barren household (20:17). The barrenness motif (<em>ʿăqārāh</em>, H6135, barren, one who is rootless/childless) connects Sarah, Rebekah, Rachel, Hannah, Elizabeth — the line of covenant continuity runs through women whose barrenness is overcome by divine intervention, not natural fertility.</p>""",
    "22": """<p><strong>wayyitroṣṣĕṣû habbānîm bĕqirbāh</strong> — "The children struggled within her." The Hithpolel of <em>rāṣaṣ</em> (H7533, to crush, bruise, oppress) — an unusual verbal form suggesting violent struggle, not mere movement; the Hithpolel adds reciprocity: they were crushing each other. The word is used in Judg 9:53 for crushing a skull and in Eccl 12:6 for a wheel broken. Rebekah's distress is linguistically grounded: this is not normal fetal movement. <em>Wattēleḵ liḏrōš ʾet-YHWH</em> — "and she went to inquire of YHWH." The verb <em>dāraš</em> (H1875, to seek, inquire, consult) is the standard term for consulting a divine oracle or prophet (1 Sam 9:9; 1 Kgs 22:8; 2 Kgs 8:8; Isa 55:6). Rebekah's inquiry is a prophetic consultation; the oracle she receives (v23) is the interpretive key for the entire Jacob-Esau narrative.</p>""",
    "23": """<p><strong>šĕnê gôyim bĕḇiṭnēḵ ûšĕnê leʾummîm mimmēʿayiḵ yippārēḏû ûleʾōm miḵleʾōm yeʾĕmāṣ wĕraḇ yaʿăḇōḏ ṣāʿîr</strong> — "Two nations are in your womb, two peoples shall be separated from within you; one people shall be stronger than the other, and the older shall serve the younger." The oracle uses both <em>gôyim</em> (nations, H1471 — foreign peoples, Gentiles) and <em>leʾummîm</em> (peoples, H3816 — a rarer, more poetic term); the pair creates a formal parallelism. <em>Yippārēḏû</em> (Niphal imperfect of <em>pāraḏ</em>, to be separated) — from within the womb, separation is already decreed. The climactic line <em>wĕraḇ yaʿăḇōḏ ṣāʿîr</em> — "the elder/great shall serve the younger/small" — is the oracle's punch: <em>raḇ</em> (great, elder, older) will serve <em>ṣāʿîr</em> (small, younger, lesser). Paul cites this oracle in Rom 9:10-12 as the clearest OT statement of unconditional election: the oracle is given before the twins are born, "not because of works but because of him who calls."</p>""",
    "24": """<p><strong>wĕhinnēh tôʾmîm bĕḇiṭnāh</strong> — "And behold, there were twins in her womb." The exclamatory <em>hinnēh</em> ("behold!") marks this as the fulfillment-surprise: Rebekah received a word about two nations, and now the physical reality is revealed — twins. The word <em>tĕʾômîm</em> (H8380, twins) — from the root <em>tāʾam</em> (to be double, to be paired) — is used here and in 38:27 (Tamar's twins Perez and Zerah). The twin births in Genesis (Jacob/Esau, Perez/Zerah) both involve reversals of the firstborn's rights — Esau's birthright passes to Jacob, and Perez pushes past Zerah in the birth canal. The pattern of twin-births-with-reversals is structurally significant in the covenant genealogy.</p>""",
    "25": """<p><strong>admōnî kullô kĕʾadderet śēʿār wayyiqrĕʾû šĕmô ʿēśāw</strong> — "The first came out red/ruddy, all of him like a hairy mantle, and they called his name Esau." Two wordplays operate simultaneously: (1) <em>admōnî</em> (ruddy, reddish, H132) plays on <em>ʾĕḏôm</em> (Edom, H123), the name of Esau's descendants and the land they inhabit; (2) <em>śēʿār</em> (hairy, H8181) plays on <em>Śēʿîr</em> (Seir, H8165), the mountainous region that becomes Edom's homeland. Both wordplays are made explicit in 25:30 (Edom = red) and 32:3/36:8 (Seir = Esau's territory). The name <em>ʿēśāw</em> itself is of uncertain etymology — "made/done" from <em>ʿāśāh</em> (to make/do) has been proposed, but this is not certain.</p>""",
    "26": """<p><strong>wĕyādô ʾōḥezet bĕʿăqēḇ ʿēśāw wayyiqrāʾ šĕmô yaʿăqōḇ</strong> — "and his hand had grasped Esau's heel, and his name was called Jacob." <em>ʾĒqeḇ</em> (H6119, heel) — the name Jacob (<em>yaʿăqōḇ</em>) is a paronomasia (wordplay) on this word: <em>yaʿăqōḇ</em> = "one who seizes the heel" or, from the related verb <em>ʿāqaḇ</em> (H6117), "one who supplants/trips up/circumvents by the heel." The two semantic valences (heel-holder vs. supplanter) are both operative: the physical act of holding the heel in the womb becomes the characteristic description of Jacob's method of operating — grasping what belongs to another by cunning rather than by right. Esau makes this explicit in 27:36: <em>wayyaʿqĕḇēnî zeh paʿămayim</em> — "has he not supplanted me these two times?" — using the verb <em>ʿāqaḇ</em>. Hosea 12:3 picks up the wordplay: "In the womb he took his brother by the heel, and in his manhood he strove with God."</p>""",
    "27": """<p><strong>wayyiggĕḏal hanaʿarîm wayhî ʿēśāw ʾîš yōḏēaʿ ṣayid ʾîš śāḏeh wĕyaʿăqōḇ ʾîš tām yōšēḇ ʾohālîm</strong> — "the boys grew up and Esau became a skillful hunter, a man of the field, while Jacob was a quiet man, dwelling in tents." The characterizations are carefully crafted: <em>yōḏēaʿ ṣayid</em> ("knower of hunt") uses <em>yāḏaʿ</em> (H3045, to know) in a skilled-mastery sense. Esau is man of the open country (<em>śāḏeh</em>, field/open land) — the same word for the uncultivated land contrasted with settled cultivation. Jacob is <em>tām</em> (H8535, complete, blameless, whole) — the same word for Noah (6:9) and Abraham (17:1: <em>tāmîm</em>); not moral perfection but integrity of character. <em>Yōšēḇ ʾohālîm</em> ("tent-dweller") marks Jacob as the pastoral, settled type, contrasting with Esau's roving hunter character.</p>""",
    "28": """<p><strong>wayyeʾĕhab yiṣḥāq ʾet-ʿēśāw kî-ṣayid bĕpîw wĕriqāh ʾōheḇet ʾet-yaʿăqōḇ</strong> — "Isaac loved Esau, for game was in his mouth, but Rebekah loved Jacob." The verb <em>ʾāhaḇ</em> (H157, to love) is used for the parental love that generates the family conflict of the next chapters. The motivation for Isaac's love is startling: <em>kî-ṣayid bĕpîw</em> — "because game was in his mouth" — the love is grounded in sensory pleasure (wild game). This parallels the materiality of the birthright scene in vv29-34 where Esau's physical hunger drives a covenant decision. Rebekah's love for Jacob lacks this kind of appetitive explanation — the narrator leaves her motive unspecified, which may suggest it was grounded in the oracle she received (v23).</p>""",
    "29": """<p><strong>wayyāzeḏ yaʿăqōḇ nāzîḏ wayyāḇōʾ ʿēśāw min-haśśāḏeh wĕhûʾ ʿāyēp</strong> — "Jacob was cooking stew when Esau came in from the field, and he was exhausted." <em>Nāzîḏ</em> (H5138, stew/broth/pottage) — from the root <em>zîḏ</em> (H2102, to boil, to be presumptuous/arrogant); the same root is used in Exod 18:11 and Neh 9:10,16 for "presumptuously" acting. The double meaning (cooked presumptuous broth) may be a deliberate wordplay — Jacob's cooking is itself an act of presumptuous calculation. <em>ʿĀyēp</em> (H5889, exhausted, faint, weary) — physically drained from the hunt; Esau's physical state will govern his decision. The contrast between Jacob's indoor cooking and Esau's outdoor hunting sets up the exchange.</p>""",
    "30": """<p><strong>haʾăṭîṭēnî nāʾ min-hāʾāḏōm hāʾāḏōm hazzeh kî ʿāyēp ʾānōḵî</strong> — "Let me eat some of that red stuff — that red stuff — for I am exhausted!" The demand is grammatically crude: <em>haʾăṭîṭēnî</em> = "let me swallow" (H3938, a rare verb for gulping/swallowing quickly) — not "give me" but "pour it into me." The reduplication <em>hāʾāḏōm hāʾāḏōm</em> (the red, the red) shows impatience and tunnel-vision; Esau does not even name what he wants — just "that red stuff." <em>ʿal-kēn qārāʾ-šĕmô ʾĕḏôm</em> — "therefore his name was called Edom" — the etiological note makes the link explicit: Esau = Edom; the red demand = the red people. The wordplay is phonological: <em>ʾāḏōm</em> (red) → <em>ʾĕḏôm</em> (Edom).</p>""",
    "31": """<p><strong>miḵrāh kāyôm ʾet-bĕḵōrātĕḵā lî</strong> — "Sell me today your birthright." <em>Bĕḵōrāh</em> (H1062, birthright, primogeniture right) — the legal bundle of rights belonging to the firstborn, including double inheritance (Deut 21:17 specifies the double portion) and family leadership authority. The imperative <em>miḵrāh</em> (sell!) is from <em>māḵar</em> (H4376, to sell, transfer ownership by transaction). Jacob frames the exchange as a commercial transaction. The word <em>kāyôm</em> ("today") specifies immediacy — the sale is to be consummated now, not deferred. Jacob's timing is calculated: Esau is vulnerable in his exhaustion and hunger.</p>""",
    "32": """<p><strong>hinnēh ʾānōḵî hôlēḵ lāmût wĕlāmmāh-zeh lî bĕḵōrāh</strong> — "Behold, I am about to die! What good is the birthright to me?" Esau's response elevates hunger to mortal threat — <em>hôlēḵ lāmût</em> ("going to die") is hyperbole, as the narrator will clarify in v34 by noting that Esau ate, drank, rose, and went his way. The rhetorical question <em>wĕlāmmāh-zeh lî bĕḵōrāh</em> expresses the logic of immediate gratification over long-term covenant inheritance. Esau is reasoning correctly within his own value framework: if you die, birthright has no value. The flaw is the premise — he is not dying.</p>""",
    "33": """<p><strong>hiššāḇĕʿāh lî kāyôm wayyiššāḇaʿ lô wayyimkōr ʾet-bĕḵōrātô lĕyaʿăqōḇ</strong> — "Swear to me today. And he swore to him, and sold his birthright to Jacob." The verb <em>šāḇaʿ</em> (H7650, to swear, to take an oath) derives from the root <em>šeḇa</em> (seven) — to swear was literally "to seven oneself" or to repeat a solemn formula seven times. An oath (<em>šĕḇûʿāh</em>) made the transaction legally binding and irrevocable under covenant norms — this is why Esau's subsequent attempts to recover the birthright are futile (27:36). <em>Wayyimkōr</em> (and he sold) — the completed sale; the birthright has legally transferred. The oath transforms what might have been a casual exchange into a permanent legal act.</p>""",
    "34": """<p><strong>wayyiḇez ʿēśāw ʾet-habbĕḵōrāh</strong> — "And Esau despised the birthright." The verb <em>bāzāh</em> (H959, to despise, disesteem, treat as worthless) — the narrator's verdict on Esau's action. The word is used for showing contempt for the covenant (Num 15:31, "despised the word of YHWH"), for despising a parent (Prov 15:20), and for despising YHWH himself (1 Sam 2:30; 2 Sam 12:10). The narrator does not say Jacob sinned by purchasing; the ethical verdict is entirely on Esau for his contempt of the covenantal birthright. This is the evaluation the NT picks up in Heb 12:16: Esau is called <em>bébēlos</em> (profane, common, secular) — one who treats the sacred as ordinary.</p>"""
  },
  "26": {
    "1": """<p><strong>wayhî rāʿāḇ bāʾāreṣ miḷḷĕḇad hārāʿāḇ hārīʾšôn ʾăšer hāyāh bîmê ʾaḇrāhām</strong> — "Now there was a famine in the land, besides the earlier famine that was in the days of Abraham." The narrator's parenthetical comparison sets up the structural parallel: Abraham went to Egypt in a famine (12:10); Isaac is told not to go (v2). The phrase <em>miḷḷĕḇad</em> (besides, apart from) explicitly distinguishes this famine from Abraham's, preventing the reader from conflating the episodes. The parallel invites comparison: Isaac's response to the same crisis will differ from his father's, and the differences are theologically instructive.</p>""",
    "2": """<p><strong>wayyērāʾ ʾēlāyw YHWH wayyōʾmer ʾal-tēreḏ miṣrāymāh</strong> — "YHWH appeared to him and said, 'Do not go down to Egypt.'" The theophany formula <em>wayyērāʾ ʾēlāyw YHWH</em> (YHWH appeared to him) — Niphal of <em>rāʾāh</em> — is the same form used for theophanies to Abraham (12:7; 17:1; 18:1). Isaac's first recorded direct encounter with YHWH begins with the prohibition against the Egypt option. The command <em>ʾal-tēreḏ miṣrāymāh</em> (do not go down to Egypt) reverses the Abraham pattern deliberately — the covenant land is where Isaac is to remain, even in famine. The same directive will be given to Jacob with a different result (46:3-4): Jacob is told to go down; Isaac is told to stay. The covenant's geographical particularity is being worked out differently in each generation.</p>""",
    "3": """<p><strong>gûr bāʾāreṣ hazzōʾt wĕʾehyeh ʿimmĕḵā ûʾăḇārĕḵekā</strong> — "Sojourn in this land, and I will be with you and will bless you." The verb <em>gûr</em> (H1481, to sojourn, live as a resident alien) — Abraham used the same term for his own status in Canaan (23:4, <em>gēr</em>). Isaac is told to sojourn, not settle permanently — he remains a temporary resident in the land of promise. The divine-presence formula <em>ʾehyeh ʿimmĕḵā</em> ("I will be with you") is the covenant presence formula that recurs throughout the patriarchal narratives (28:15; 31:3; 48:21) and becomes foundational for the Exodus (<em>ʾehyeh ʾăšer ʾehyeh</em>, "I am who I am/I will be what I will be," Exod 3:14).</p>""",
    "4": """<p><strong>wĕhirbêtî ʾet-zarʿăḵā kĕkoḵĕḇê haššāmayim wĕnātattî lĕzarʿăḵā ʾēt kol-hāʾărāṣōt hāʾēl wĕhitbārăḵû bĕzarʿăḵā kol gôyê hāʾāreṣ</strong> — "I will multiply your seed as the stars of the sky, and I will give to your seed all these lands, and through your seed all the nations of the earth shall bless themselves." The three-element promise to Abraham (12:2-3; 15:5; 17:4-8) is now confirmed to Isaac: multiplication of seed (stars), land, and blessing to all nations. <em>Zarʿăḵā</em> (your seed) is the covenant-continuity term throughout Genesis — the singular collective noun that will carry the Abrahamic promise forward. The blessing formula <em>wĕhitbārăḵû bĕzarʿăḵā</em> uses the Hithpael of <em>bāraḵ</em> — reflexive: "shall bless themselves by your seed."</p>""",
    "5": """<p><strong>ʿēqeḇ ʾăšer-šāmaʿ ʾaḇrāhām bĕqōlî wayyišmōr mišmartî miṣwōtay ḥuqqôtay wĕtôrōtāy</strong> — "because Abraham obeyed my voice and kept my charge, my commandments, my statutes, and my laws." Four terms accumulate for Abraham's obedience: <em>mišmeret</em> (charge, watch-keeping duty), <em>miṣwāh</em> (commandment, explicit directive), <em>ḥuqqāh</em> (statute, engraved ordinance), and <em>tôrāh</em> (instruction, law). The same tetrad appears in Lev 18:30; 22:9 for Israel's covenant obligations. This is remarkable: Abraham is credited with keeping the Mosaic-sounding categories of covenant law before Sinai — not because the Mosaic law existed yet, but because the covenant relationship with YHWH has always involved obedient hearing (<em>šāmaʿ bĕqôlî</em>, to hear/obey my voice). The grounding of Isaac's blessing in Abraham's past obedience shows that covenant blessing is cumulative and transmittable.</p>""",
    "6": """<p><strong>wayyēšeḇ yiṣḥāq bigrār</strong> — "So Isaac settled in Gerar." The bare compliance statement after the theophany and extensive covenant promise is a narrative device signaling immediate, simple obedience. Isaac stays where he is told to stay; his obedience is uncontested at this stage of the narrative. Gerar is the Philistine territory where Abraham also sojourned with Abimelech (20:1-18) — the geographic repetition reinforces the structural parallel between the Abraham and Isaac episodes in this chapter. The same place, the same king (Abimelech — likely a dynastic title rather than the same individual), the same deception, and the same resolution.</p>""",
    "7": """<p><strong>wayyišʾălû ʾanĕšê hammāqôm lĕʾišĕtô wayyōʾmer ʾăḥōtî hîʾ kî yārēʾ lēʾmōr ʾišĕtî</strong> — "The men of the place asked him about his wife. He said, 'She is my sister,' for he feared to say, 'She is my wife.'" The wife-sister deception occurs three times in Genesis (12:10-20 for Abraham in Egypt; 20:1-18 for Abraham with Abimelech; here for Isaac with the same Abimelech). The repetition is structurally deliberate: each patriarch faces the same temptation (protect yourself by endangering your wife) and each chooses the same deception. <em>Yārēʾ</em> (feared) — Isaac's motivation is stated explicitly: fear. The fear is legitimate (beautiful wives were dangerous assets), but the solution — deception — compromises the covenant wife's safety for the husband's benefit.</p>""",
    "8": """<p><strong>wayyaṣṣēp ʾăḇîmeleḵ melek pĕlištîm bĕʿaḏ haḥallôn wayyarʾ wĕhinnēh yiṣḥāq mĕṣaḥēq ʾēt riqāh ʾišĕtô</strong> — "Abimelech king of the Philistines looked out a window and saw — and behold — Isaac laughing/sporting with Rebekah his wife." The key word is <em>mĕṣaḥēq</em> — Piel participle of <em>ṣāḥaq</em> (to laugh, play, sport, caress) — the same root as Isaac's own name (<em>yiṣḥāq</em> = "he laughs"). The text makes the wordplay unavoidable: <em>yiṣḥāq</em> was seen <em>mĕṣaḥēq</em> — "Isaac was Isaacing." The Piel of <em>ṣāḥaq</em> has a range from laughing to playing to sexual intimacy (cf. 39:14,17 where Potiphar's wife uses it to accuse Joseph). The context of a husband and wife makes the sexual nuance primary — Abimelech concludes they are married from this intimate behavior, not from overhearing a conversation.</p>""",
    "9": """<p><strong>ʾāḵēn hinnēh ʾišĕtĕḵā hîʾ wĕʾêk ʾāmartā ʾăḥōtî hîʾ</strong> — "She is clearly your wife! How did you say, 'She is my sister'?" The adverb <em>ʾāḵēn</em> (surely, indeed, clearly) marks Abimelech's conclusion as certain — what he saw was unambiguous evidence of marriage. The king's challenge is direct and legitimate: Isaac's deception endangered the king's household by the potential of one of his men taking Isaac's wife — which would constitute adultery (the same concern Abimelech expressed to Abraham in 20:3-6). Isaac's response, "I thought I might die on account of her" (<em>pen-ʾāmût ʿālehā</em>), acknowledges the fear motivation without defending the deception.</p>""",
    "10": """<p><strong>mah-zōʾt ʿāśîtā llānû kĕmĕʿaṭ šāḵaḇ ʾaḥaḏ hāʿām ʾet-ʾišĕtĕḵā wĕhēḇêʾtā ʿālênû ʾāšām</strong> — "What is this you have done to us? One of the people might easily have lain with your wife, and you would have brought guilt upon us." <em>ʾĀšām</em> (H817, guilt, guilt-offering, offense requiring restitution) — in Levitical law the <em>ʾāšām</em> is the guilt-offering required when one has wronged another party and must make restitution (Lev 5:14-6:7). Abimelech's use of the term shows his awareness that lying with another man's wife is a legally accountable wrong. The king of the Philistines is applying the principle that YHWH applied to him in 20:6 — the same covenantal moral framework governs pagan as well as covenant interactions.</p>""",
    "11": """<p><strong>wayyĕṣaw ʾăḇîmeleḵ ʾet-kol-hāʿām lēʾmōr hannōgēaʿ bāʾîš hazzeh ûḇĕʾišĕtô môt yûmāt</strong> — "Abimelech commanded all the people: 'Whoever touches this man or his wife shall certainly be put to death.'" The death formula <em>môt yûmāt</em> (infinitive absolute + imperfect = "dying he shall die," emphatic death penalty) — the same formula used in the capital case laws of the Torah (Exod 21:12-17; Lev 20:2,9-16). Abimelech's protection order over Isaac and Rebekah is more emphatic than the ordinary protection a guest might expect. It reflects both his personal moral concern (expressed in v10) and the practical recognition that YHWH is with Isaac (which he will state explicitly in v28).</p>""",
    "12": """<p><strong>wayyizraʿ yiṣḥāq bāʾāreṣ hahîʾ wayyimṣāʾ baššānāh hahîʾ mēʾāh šĕʿārîm wayyĕḇāreḵēhû YHWH</strong> — "Isaac sowed in that land and reaped in that year a hundredfold, and YHWH blessed him." <em>Mēʾāh šĕʿārîm</em> (a hundred gates/measures) — the <em>šaʿar</em> here is a grain measure, not a city gate: "a hundredfold." In the ancient world a 10:1 return on seed was considered outstanding; 100:1 is miraculous. The causal <em>wayyĕḇāreḵēhû YHWH</em> (YHWH blessed him) — the narrator attributes the abundance directly to covenant blessing, not to Isaac's agricultural skill. The abundance in the famine year is a sign of YHWH's presence with the covenant heir in the land he commanded him to stay in.</p>""",
    "13": """<p><strong>wayyigdal hāʾîš wayyēlek hālôḵ wĕgāḏēl ʿaḏ kî-gāḏal mĕʾōḏ</strong> — "The man became great, and kept growing greater until he became very great." The Qal perfect <em>gāḏal</em> + the idiom <em>hālôḵ wĕgāḏēl</em> (going and growing) — the infinitive absolute of <em>hālaḵ</em> combined with the Qal participle of <em>gāḏal</em> creates the picture of continuous, ongoing growth. The same construction appears in 2 Sam 5:10 for David: "David grew and grew" (<em>hālôḵ wĕgāḏôl</em>). The threefold use of <em>gāḏal</em> in this verse (became great / growing greater / very great) is emphatic accumulation — the narrator insists on the magnitude of Isaac's prosperity to set up the Philistine envy in v14.</p>""",
    "14": """<p><strong>wayhî-lô miqnēh-ṣōʾn ûmiqnēh-ḇāqār waʿăḇuddāh rabbāh wayyĕqannĕʾû ʾōtô pĕlištîm</strong> — "He had flocks and herds and a great household, and the Philistines envied him." <em>Qānnāʾ</em> (Piel of <em>qānāʾ</em>, H7065, to be jealous/envious) — a strong word; the same root describes God's "jealousy" (<em>ʾēl qannāʾ</em>, Exod 20:5; 34:14) and the jealousy that drove Joseph's brothers to sell him (Acts 7:9). The Philistines' envy is the socio-political pressure that generates the expulsion of v16 and the well-disputes of vv19-21. Covenant blessing in the land of the foreigner creates tension — a pattern that recurs from Joseph in Egypt to Israel in Egypt to Daniel in Babylon.</p>""",
    "15": """<p><strong>wĕkol-habbĕʾērōt ʾăšer ḥāpĕrû ʿaḇdê ʾāḇîw bîmê ʾaḇrāhām ʾāḇîw sittĕmûm pĕlištîm wayyĕmalĕʾûm ʿāpār</strong> — "Now all the wells that his father's servants had dug in the days of his father Abraham, the Philistines stopped them up and filled them with dirt." The destruction of wells in the ancient Near East was an act of war and a deliberate denial of future habitation rights — wells represented permanent water-claim in a semi-arid landscape. The Philistines' actions against Abraham's wells are an erasure of the patriarchal covenant presence in the land. Isaac's response (v18) — reopening the same wells and giving them the same names — is an act of covenant reaffirmation: reclaiming what was his father's in the covenant territory.</p>""",
    "16": """<p><strong>ʿāṣamt mimmennû mĕʾōḏ</strong> — "you have become too powerful for us." The verb <em>ʿāṣam</em> (H6105, to be numerous, strong, mighty) — the same verb used for Israel's multiplication in Egypt (Exod 1:7,20) and for YHWH's mighty arm (Deut 9:29; 26:8). The Philistines' fear of Isaac's growing power parallels Pharaoh's fear of Israel's growth (Exod 1:9-10: "the people of Israel are more numerous and stronger than we"). Both situations involve the covenant people's prosperity creating host-nation anxiety that leads to expulsion or oppression. The pattern of blessing → growth → host-fear → expulsion is a recurring structure in the covenant narrative.</p>""",
    "17": """<p><strong>wayyēlek miššām yiṣḥāq wayyaḥan bĕnaḥal gĕrār wayyēšeḇ šām</strong> — "So Isaac moved away from there and camped in the Valley of Gerar and settled there." The verbs sequence — moved (<em>hālaḵ</em>), camped (<em>ḥānāh</em>), settled (<em>yāšaḇ</em>) — follow the patriarchal movement pattern of Abraham (12:9; 13:18; 21:34). Isaac's movement into the valley is a compromise: he leaves the city but stays in the region, pressing the question of how far he must go before he finds undisputed space. The Valley of Gerar (<em>naḥal gĕrār</em>) is a wadi/watercourse — the kind of terrain where digging wells would be productive, setting up the disputes of vv19-21.</p>""",
    "18": """<p><strong>wayyāšāb yiṣḥāq wayyaḥpōr ʾet-bĕʾĕrōt hammayim ʾăšer ḥāpĕrû bîmê ʾaḇrāhām ʾāḇîw</strong> — "Isaac dug again the wells of water that had been dug in the days of his father Abraham." <em>Ḥāpar</em> (H2658, to dig, bore into) — the verb used for digging wells throughout this chapter (vv18-22,25,32). Isaac's reversion to Abraham's wells is a legal and covenantal claim: these are not new wells but the restoration of Abraham's property rights. <em>Wayyiqrāʾ lāhen šēmôt kĕšēmōt ʾăšer-qārāʾ lāhen ʾāḇîw</em> — "he gave them the same names that his father had given them" — the renaming is continuity of ownership claim. Abraham's names mark the history; Isaac's repetition of those names asserts the covenant inheritance is unbroken even through the Philistine erasure.</p>""",
    "19": """<p><strong>wayyeḥpĕrû ʿaḇdê-yiṣḥāq bannāḥal wayyimṣĕʾû šām bĕʾēr mayim ḥayyîm</strong> — "Isaac's servants dug in the valley and found there a well of living/fresh water." <em>Mayim ḥayyîm</em> (living water, flowing spring water) — <em>ḥāy</em> (H2416, alive, living) — the phrase distinguishes spring-fed, flowing water from cistern water (stored rainwater). Living water was the highest quality — pure, fresh, reliable — and appears throughout OT legislation (Lev 14:5,50; 15:13; Num 19:17) and wisdom/prophetic literature (Jer 2:13; 17:13; Zech 14:8). Jesus's use of "living water" in John 4:10-14 and 7:38 is charged with this OT background — the new covenant blessing is described in the language of the freshest, purest, most life-sustaining water.</p>""",
    "20": """<p><strong>wayyĕrîḇû rōʿê gĕrār ʿim-rōʿê yiṣḥāq lēʾmōr lānû hāmāyim wayyiqrāʾ šēm-habbĕʾēr ʿēśeq kî hitʿassĕqû ʿimmô</strong> — "The herdsmen of Gerar quarreled with Isaac's herdsmen, saying, 'The water is ours!' So he named the well Esek, because they disputed with him." <em>ʿĒśeq</em> (H6219, contention, dispute) — from the root <em>ʿāsaq</em> (to dispute, press a claim). The naming convention in vv20-22 is an etiology: each well's name records what happened there. Isaac's response to the dispute is to move on (<em>wayyelek miššām</em>, v21) — he does not fight for the well. This patience under repeated opposition is Isaac's characteristic response throughout the chapter, culminating in the Rehoboth statement of v22.</p>""",
    "21": """<p><strong>wayyaḥpĕrû bĕʾēr ʾaḥeret wayyĕrîḇû gam-ʿāleyhā wayyiqrāʾ šĕmāh śiṭnāh</strong> — "They dug another well, and they quarreled over that one also, and he named it Sitnah." <em>Śiṭnāh</em> (H7855, opposition, hostility, accusation) — from the root <em>śāṭan</em> (H7853, to oppose, to be an adversary), the root that gives the title "Satan" (the Adversary). The naming of a well "Adversary/Accusation" reflects the experience of enmity that was purely hostile and unjust — not a legitimate competing claim but pure opposition. The progression Esek (contention) → Sitnah (adversarial hostility) shows escalation. Isaac again moves without fighting back.</p>""",
    "22": """<p><strong>wayyaʿtēq miššām wayyaḥpōr bĕʾēr ʾaḥeret wĕlōʾ rāḇû ʿāleyhā wayyiqrāʾ šĕmāh rĕḥōḇôt wayyōʾmer kî-ʿattāh hirḥîḇ YHWH lānû ûpārînû bāʾāreṣ</strong> — "He moved from there and dug another well, and they did not quarrel over it. He named it Rehoboth, saying, 'For now YHWH has made room for us, and we will be fruitful in the land.'" <em>Rĕḥōḇôt</em> (H7344, wide places, spacious areas) — from <em>rāḥaḇ</em> (H7337, to be wide, to make room). Isaac interprets the cessation of conflict as divine provision of space — <em>hirḥîḇ YHWH lānû</em> ("YHWH has made room for us"). The movement from Esek to Sitnah to Rehoboth is a theological narrative of patient endurance yielding to divine provision: God does not give the space at first but creates it through the progression of trials. <em>ûpārînû bāʾāreṣ</em> — "we will be fruitful in the land" — <em>pārāh</em> (H6509, to be fruitful) echoes the creation blessing (1:28) and the Abrahamic promise (17:6) — covenant fruitfulness finally has room to express itself.</p>""",
    "23": """<p><strong>wayyaʿal miššām bĕʾēr šāḇaʿ</strong> — "From there he went up to Beersheba." The movement <em>wayyaʿal</em> (went up) — the directional opposite of <em>yāraḏ</em> (to go down) — moves from the lowland Valley of Gerar back toward the highland of Beersheba, the location of the patriarchal covenant with Abimelech (21:22-34) and the altar of Abraham (21:33). The journey to Beersheba is a movement toward the sacred site of covenant history, and the theophany of v24 confirms this — YHWH appears at the place of covenant establishment.</p>""",
    "24": """<p><strong>ʾānōḵî ʾĕlōhê ʾaḇrāhām ʾāḇîḵā ʾal-tîrāʾ kî-ʾittĕḵā ʾānōḵî ûḇēraḵtîḵā wĕhirḇêtî ʾet-zarʿăḵā baʿăḇûr ʾaḇrāhām ʿaḇdî</strong> — "I am the God of your father Abraham. Do not be afraid, for I am with you; I will bless you and multiply your seed, for the sake of Abraham my servant." The self-identification formula <em>ʾānōḵî ʾĕlōhê ʾāḇîḵā</em> — "I am the God of your father" — is the covenantal self-introduction (cf. 28:13; 31:42; 32:9; Exod 3:6). The fear formula <em>ʾal-tîrāʾ</em> (do not be afraid) accompanies every major patriarchal covenant encounter (15:1; 21:17; 26:24; 28:13; 46:3). <em>Baʿăḇûr ʾaḇrāhām ʿaḇdî</em> — "for the sake of Abraham my servant" — the covenant benefits to Isaac are explicitly grounded in Abraham's prior covenant status. The title <em>ʿeḇeḏ</em> (servant) for Abraham is the highest honorific in the OT covenant vocabulary (also used for Moses, Joshua, David).</p>""",
    "25": """<p><strong>wayyiḇen šām mizḇēaḥ wayyiqrāʾ bĕšēm YHWH wayyeṭ-šām ʾohŏlô wayyikrû šām ʿaḇdê-yiṣḥāq bĕʾēr</strong> — "He built an altar there and called on the name of YHWH, and he pitched his tent there, and Isaac's servants dug a well there." The three-fold covenant response — altar, calling on YHWH's name, tent — mirrors the Abraham pattern exactly: Abraham built altars at Shechem (12:7), Bethel (12:8 — also "called on the name"), Mamre (13:18), and Beersheba (21:33). Isaac's replication of these covenant markers at Beersheba is a conscious continuation of the patriarchal covenant practice. The altar (<em>mizḇēaḥ</em>) is the formal site of encounter; calling on the name (<em>qāraʾ bĕšēm YHWH</em>) is the covenant worship formula; the tent marks covenant residence; the well marks covenant provision.</p>""",
    "26": """<p><strong>waʾăḇîmeleḵ hālaḵ ʾēlāyw migĕrār waʾăḥuzzat mērēʿēhû ûpîḵōl śar-ṣĕḇāʾô</strong> — "Abimelech came to him from Gerar with Ahuzzath his adviser and Phicol the commander of his forces." The same Abimelech-Phicol pair appeared in the Abraham covenant (21:22,32). If these are the same individuals, 80+ years have passed — more likely "Abimelech" is a Philistine dynastic title (like "Pharaoh" for Egypt) and "Phicol" similarly. <em>Mēraʿēhû</em> — "his friend/companion" (from <em>rēaʿ</em>, H7453, friend, associate, companion) — Ahuzzath is Abimelech's personal advisor, the king's inner council.</p>""",
    "27": """<p><strong>lāmmāh bāʾtem ʾēlay wĕʾattem śĕnēʾtem ʾōtî wattĕšalĕḥûnî mēʾittĕkem</strong> — "Why have you come to me, since you hated me and sent me away from you?" Isaac's challenge uses <em>śānēʾ</em> (H8130, to hate, to be hostile toward) — a strong term for covenant enmity. Isaac's memory of the Philistines' hostility (v15 — stopping his father's wells; v16 — expelling him) grounds his suspicion. The question is not rude but honest — Isaac names the prior hostility before engaging with the covenant request. This directness is not typical of ANE diplomatic discourse, which would normally open with politeness; Isaac's frankness shows both his awareness of the history and his willingness to negotiate from a position of truth.</p>""",
    "28": """<p><strong>rāʾôh rāʾînû kî-hāyāh YHWH ʿimmāḵ</strong> — "We have plainly seen that YHWH was with you." The emphatic construction <em>rāʾôh rāʾînû</em> (Qal infinitive absolute + perfect = "seeing we have seen") — the doubled form intensifies: their perception is certain, observed, undeniable. The basis for Abimelech's treaty request is the observation of divine favor: YHWH's presence with Isaac is so evident that even the Philistine king can name it. This pattern — covenant people's prosperity making YHWH's presence observable to Gentile rulers — recurs in Joseph (39:3), Moses (Exod 18:9-11), and the missional theology of Isa 2:2-4 and 60:1-3. The Gentile's recognition of YHWH's covenantal presence is the basis for covenant diplomacy.</p>""",
    "29": """<p><strong>ʾim-taʿăśeh ʿimmānû rāʿāh kaʾăšer lōʾ nĕgaʿnûḵā wĕkaʾăšer ʿāśînû ʿimmĕḵā raq-ṭôḇ wattĕšallĕḥăḵā bĕšālôm wĕʾattāh ʿattāh bĕrûḵ YHWH</strong> — "that you will not do us harm, just as we have not touched you and have done to you nothing but good and sent you away in peace. You are now the blessed of the LORD." The Philistines' self-description of their conduct is selective (Isaac experienced their stopping his wells and expelling him), but the diplomatic formula focuses on the present — they are appealing for treaty on the basis of not having physically harmed Isaac. <em>ʿAttāh bĕrûḵ YHWH</em> — "you are blessed of YHWH" — the Philistine king applies the covenant title to Isaac; the blessing Isaac carries is so visible that his adversary names it. The phrase will return in the Boaz-Ruth narrative (Ruth 3:10) and the Psalms (Ps 115:15; 128:4).</p>""",
    "30": """<p><strong>wayyaʿaś lāhem mišteh wayyōʾkĕlû wayyišĕtû</strong> — "He made them a feast and they ate and drank." The covenant meal (<em>mišteh</em>, H4960, feast/drinking occasion) seals the treaty: in ANE covenant practice, eating together was the ratification of an agreement — the shared table bound the parties morally and socially. Compare Abraham's covenant meal with Abimelech (21:27-31) and Jacob's covenant meal with Laban (31:54). The pattern of covenant ratification through shared eating connects this episode to the broader covenant tradition and anticipates the covenant-meal theology of Exod 24:11 and the Lord's Supper.</p>""",
    "31": """<p><strong>wayyaškimû babbōqer wayyiššāḇĕʿû ʾîš lĕʾāḥîw wayyĕšallĕḥēm yiṣḥāq wayyēlĕḵû mēʾittô bĕšālôm</strong> — "Early in the morning they swore an oath to one another. Then Isaac sent them off, and they went away from him in peace." <em>Wayyaškimû</em> (they rose early) — early rising for the covenant oath ratification parallels Abraham's early rising for covenant acts (22:3: the Moriah journey; 21:14: sending away Hagar). The oath (<em>šĕḇûʿāh</em>) formally sealed the covenant begun by the meal of v30. <em>Bĕšālôm</em> (in peace, in wholeness) — the word <em>šālôm</em> (H7965) here means covenant-peace, the wholeness of relations between two parties who have formalized mutual non-aggression. The Philistines leave in <em>šālôm</em> — the same word Isaac's servants will use for Beersheba (Beer-sheba = seven/oath).</p>""",
    "32": """<p><strong>wayyōʾmĕrû lô māṣāʾnû māyim</strong> — "They said to him, 'We have found water!'" The discovery of the new well on the same day as the covenant with Abimelech is a narrative juxtaposition — covenant with man and covenant provision from God are simultaneous. The servants' report uses <em>māṣāʾ</em> (H4672, to find, to come upon) — the discovery of water is framed as finding something given rather than digging something out; the providence is credited to discovery, not to labor. The timing (same day as the treaty) invites the reader to see YHWH's provision as confirming the covenant settlement.</p>""",
    "33": """<p><strong>wayyiqrāʾ ʾōtāh šiḇʿāh ʿal-kēn šēm-hāʿîr bĕʾēr šāḇaʿ ʿaḏ hayyôm hazzeh</strong> — "He called it Shibah; therefore the name of the city has been Beersheba to this day." The place name <em>bĕʾēr šāḇaʿ</em> carries a double etymology: (1) from <em>šeḇa</em> (H7651, seven) — Abraham's covenant with Abimelech involved seven lambs as a witness (21:28-31); (2) from <em>šāḇaʿ</em> (H7650, to swear) — both the Abraham covenant (21:31) and the Isaac covenant (v31 here) involve oaths. The name encodes both "well of seven" and "well of the oath" — both etymologies are simultaneously valid, reflecting the double oath (Abraham's and Isaac's) that attach to the location. <em>ʿAḏ hayyôm hazzeh</em> ("to this day") is the narrator's confirmation that the name has persisted to his own time.</p>""",
    "34": """<p><strong>wayhî ʿēśāw ben-ʾarbāʿîm šānāh wayyiqqaḥ ʾiššāh ʾet-yĕhûḏît bat-bĕʾērî haḥittî wĕʾet-bāśmat bat-ʾêlôn haḥittî</strong> — "When Esau was forty years old, he took as wife Judith daughter of Beeri the Hittite, and Basemath daughter of Elon the Hittite." Esau's marriages at age 40 mirror Isaac's marriage age (v20). But the contrast is sharp: Isaac married within the Abrahamic family (Rebekah from Paddan Aram); Esau marries Hittite women — Canaanites, outside the covenant family. The specific identification "Hittites" (<em>ḥittî</em>) echoes the Ephron-Hittite transaction of ch 23 — the non-covenant people from whom Abraham bought the burial cave. Esau's Hittite wives represent the same pattern as the birthright sale: trading the covenant for immediate local advantage.</p>""",
    "35": """<p><strong>wattihyênāh môrat rûaḥ lĕyiṣḥāq ûlĕriqāh</strong> — "and they were a source of bitterness of spirit to Isaac and Rebekah." The idiom <em>môrat rûaḥ</em> (bitterness of spirit) — <em>mārar</em> (H4843, to be bitter) + <em>rûaḥ</em> (H7307, spirit/breath) — a grief that sits in the breath, in the inner life. The same idiom appears in 1 Sam 1:10 for Hannah's anguish. The narrative coda to ch 26 connects directly to the motivation for Rebekah's schemes in ch 27: if Esau's Hittite wives already cause Isaac and Rebekah such distress, Rebekah's actions to prevent the covenant blessing from going to Esau become more comprehensible — she fears Jacob will marry Hittite women too (27:46; 28:1-2), and the covenant line will be completely absorbed into the Canaanite population.</p>"""
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-original', 'genesis')
    before_count = sum(len(v) for v in existing.values())
    merge_comm(existing, GENESIS_ORIGINAL)
    save_comm('mkt-original', 'genesis', existing)

    result = load_comm('mkt-original', 'genesis')
    after_count = sum(len(v) for v in result.values())
    print(f'  Verses added: {after_count - before_count}')
    for ch in [25, 26]:
        ck = str(ch)
        n = len(result.get(ck, {}))
        print(f'  Ch {ch}: {n} verses present')
    total_chs = len(result)
    total_vv = sum(len(v) for v in result.values())
    print(f'  Genesis total: {total_chs} chapters, {total_vv} verses with original data')
    print('Genesis 25-26 mkt-original written.')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
